# Final Board Vote — Proposal 01: EdgeBot Tutor
**Date:** 2026-04-09
**Voting Member:** CFO (The Pragmatic Anchor)

---

## Vote: REJECT (Pending Financial Resubmission)

---

## Reasoning

The board discussion has clarified the technical and market picture considerably. Neither outcome improves my fiscal position — if anything, the group review has hardened my concerns.

### What the Group Discussion Confirmed

**From the CTO:**
- The prototype BOM is $50–70, not $35. The sub-$35 figure is a volume-pricing claim that requires a minimum run of 500–1,000 units. My risk-case unit economics (BOM ~$40 at low volume) is effectively the *base case* at launch. Gross margin at prototype scale is approximately 30–40% on a $65 retail price — below sustainable threshold.
- The 50M parameter model doesn't fit on the hardware. This is a proposal credibility failure. If the core technical claim is wrong, what else hasn't been stress-tested? The corrected architecture (classification + templated responses) is sound, but the revision is still pending — this proposal has not been updated.

**From the CMO:**
- The beachhead buyer (India/SEA homeschool co-op parent) has a willingness-to-pay of $35–60 — the lower end of my pricing scenarios. This compresses margin precisely where BOM is highest (pre-scale). The high-margin market and the target beachhead are not the same market. The CMO named this risk; it remains unmitigated.
- No recurring revenue mechanics were proposed by the CMO either. The hardware-only model is a shared concern. A "shareable progress" feature and a Discord community are retention tools, not revenue streams.

### Blocking Items Remain Unresolved

None of the five items I flagged in my prior analysis have been addressed:

| Blocking Item | Status |
|---|---|
| Prototype budget ($ and hours) | Not provided |
| Crowdfunding target amount | Not provided |
| Minimum production run quantity | Not provided |
| Recurring revenue model | Not proposed by any board member |
| Founder cash/salary assumptions | Not provided |

### The Recurring Revenue Gap Is the Deciding Factor

A one-time $65–100 hardware sale with no follow-on revenue produces an LTV:CAC ratio that is structurally below 3:1 at any realistic crowdfunding CAC ($15–40/backer). This is not a venture-backable model as written. The CMO identified retention levers (community, progress sharing, parent summaries) but none of them generate revenue. The CFO needs a recurring revenue proposal — curriculum subscription, premium lesson packs, a school seat license — before this can be presented to any investor or approved for resource commitment.

---

## Path to Approval

I will change my vote to **APPROVE** if the CEO resubmits with:

1. A Phase 1 budget with explicit line items (hardware BOM × prototype units, engineering hours, pilot logistics, crowdfunding campaign spend)
2. A crowdfunding minimum success threshold (the unit quantity required to fund a production run that achieves sub-$35 BOM)
3. One proposed recurring revenue mechanism with an LTV estimate
4. An updated proposal correcting the model architecture per the CTO's specification

This is not a rejection of the concept. The technical differentiation is real. The market gap is real. The on-device cost advantage is real. The product can be built. The business model cannot yet be evaluated.

**Revenue is reality. A plan without numbers is a vision document, not a proposal.**

---

