# CTO Final Vote — Proposal 01: EdgeBot Tutor
**Date:** 2026-04-09
**Voting Member:** CTO (The Engineering Architect)

---

## Vote: APPROVE (Conditional — Prototype Phase Only)

---

## Reasoning

My prior position was withheld pending a model architecture revision. Having reviewed the CMO and CFO analyses in full, I am moving to a conditional **APPROVE**. Here is my engineering-driven reasoning.

### The Architecture Error Is Correctable — and Already Corrected

The "~50M parameter language + classification model" claim in the original proposal is wrong. I documented this in my feasibility study with precision: the ESP32-S3 with 8 MB PSRAM cannot run any model above ~2M parameters without severe runtime degradation, and the correct Phase 1 target is **≤500K parameters, INT8 QAT-trained, classification architecture**. The corrected design — a classifier driving a finite-state machine with pre-authored templated tutor responses — is not a compromise. It is the architecturally superior design for this use case.

Critically: the correction is fully defined. I have specified the hardware decision table, the inference runtime (TFLite Micro), the training data strategy (simulation-based synthetic data), and the software stack. **There is no remaining ambiguity in the Phase 1 architecture.** Withholding a vote over a documented correction that is fully resolved in my own analysis is process theater.

### The CMO Argument Changed My Calculus

The 18–24 month competitive window is an engineering constraint, not just a marketing preference. If Makeblock, Raspberry Pi Foundation, or a well-funded Chinese hardware ODM ships an adaptive AI kit in that window, our technical moat becomes a commodity feature. The prototype phase is the only way to generate pilot data, refine the classifier, and establish a real-world feedback loop before that window closes. The prototype cost is $50–70 in hardware and a single engineer's focused sprint. The opportunity cost of delaying is orders of magnitude larger.

### Where I Align with the CFO — and Where I Diverge

The CFO is correct that the BOM-at-prototype-scale ($50–70) versus BOM-at-production-scale (<$35) gap is a real financial risk. I flagged this in my own analysis. However, the CFO's blocking items — crowdfunding target, recurring revenue model, LTV:CAC ratio — are outputs of the prototype and pilot phase, not inputs to it. You cannot model conversion rates for a product that doesn't exist. The prototype generates the data the CFO needs to complete the financial model. Blocking the prototype because the financial model is incomplete is inverting the dependency.

I also note: the on-device inference architecture eliminates recurring cloud API costs permanently. At pilot scale this is negligible; at 500,000 sessions/year it is material. This is a structural cost advantage that compounds with scale and should not be discounted in the LTV analysis.

### My Conditions for This Approval

This APPROVE is for the **prototype phase only**. It is contingent on the following engineering commitments being locked and executed before any other milestone is counted:

| Commitment | Requirement | Why It's Non-Negotiable |
|---|---|---|
| Architecture revision committed | All documentation updated: ≤500K params, INT8, QAT, classifier + FSM. "50M parameter language model" language removed everywhere. | The current proposal contains a technical error. Running engineering from a wrong spec produces wasted work. |
| Training data pipeline begins Week 1 | Synthetic simulation pipeline for motor control, PWM, and sensor error classes is the critical path. No slip. | Training data is the longest-lead item. A Week 5 start guarantees a Week 10–12 slip. |
| RP2040 dropped from all specifications | ESP32-S3 only. | RP2040 cannot run the inference workload. It is a distraction. |
| Curriculum engine scoped to linear state machine | 3 sequential modules for prototype. DAG architecture is Phase 2. | Over-engineering the curriculum engine in Phase 1 steals time from the model, which is the product. |
| Teacher dashboard deferred | No dashboard work until Phase 2. Dashboard sync protocol cannot be specified until Phase 1 data transport mechanism is chosen. | Premature dashboard work is scope creep. |
| Watchdog timer (WDT) enforced from Day 1 | Student code execution must be timeout-gated. Single register write in firmware. | Students will write infinite loops. This is not a maybe. |

### The Bottom Line

The core technical thesis is sound. The platform choice is correct. The inference strategy is correct (with revision). The training approach is defined. The timeline is achievable under correct scoping. The competitive window is real and closing.

The architecture error in the original proposal is a documentation problem, not a design flaw. The design flaw was corrected in my feasibility study. That correction is locked. We can build from it.

**Build the prototype. Run it correctly. Generate the data the CFO needs to write the financial model.**

